ng period of panic buying has also caused many stores to be cleared of non-medical products such as bottled water, vegetables, and rice.<ref name=\"scmp3048121\">{{cite web |url=https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/society/article/3048121/china-coronavirus-shelves-cleared-essentials-spread-sparks |title=Shelves cleared as coronavirus spread sparks Hong Kong panic buying |date=29 January 2020 |website=South China Morning Post |access-date=31 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130185856/https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/society/article/3048121/china-coronavirus-shelves-cleared-essentials-spread-sparks |archive-date=30 January 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> The [[Government of Hong Kong]] had its imports of face masks cancelled as global face mask stockpiles decline.<ref name=\"scmp3048332\">{{cite web |url=https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/health-environment/article/3048332/china-coronavirus-hongkongers-online-orders-masks |title=Mask orders cancelled as Hongkongers face overseas supply issues amid virus |date=31 January 2020 |website=South China Morning Post |access-date=31 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200131031715/https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/health-environment/article/3048332/china-coronavirus-hongkongers-online-orders-masks |archive-date=31 January 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn view of the coronavirus outbreak, the [[Education Bureau]] closed all kindergartens, primary schools, secondary schools, and special schools until 20 April.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/education/article/3075521/coronavirus-little-if-any-possibility-hong-kong-schools |title=Coronavirus: \u2018little, if any, possibility\u2019 Hong Kong schools resume fully on April 20, Lam says|website=SCMP |access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref> The disruption raised concerns over the situation of students due to take examinations at the end of the year, especially in light of the protest-related disruption that happened in 2019.<ref name=\"scmp3047662\">{{cite web |url=https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/education/article/3047662/china-coronavirus-hong-kong-students-face-exam-crunch |title=First protests, now virus: schools suspension could hurt those facing exams |date=26 January 2020 |website=South China Morning Post |access-date=3 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200203063457/https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/education/article/3047662/china-coronavirus-hong-kong-students-face-exam-crunch |archive-date=3 February 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 February, flag carrier [[Cathay Pacific]] requested its 27,000 employees to voluntarily take three weeks of unpaid leave by the end of June. The airline had previously reduced flights to mainland China by 90% and overall flights by 30%.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Riley |first=Charles |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/02/05/business/cathay-pacific-coronavirus/index.html |title=Cathay Pacific asks workers to take 3 weeks off without pay as the coronavirus decimates travel |date=5 February 2020 |publisher=CNN |access-date=7 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206100340/https://edition.cnn.com/2020/02/05/business/cathay-pacific-coronavirus/index.html |archive-date=6 February 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome]] (SARS)\n\n{{Portal bar|COVID-19|Hong Kong|Medicine|Viruses}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.coronavirus.gov.hk/eng/index.html Together, We Fight the Virus!]\n* [https://www.chp.gov.hk/en/index.html The Centre for Health Protection]\n*{{Commons category-inline|COVID-19 pandemic in Hong Kong}}\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n{{2019\u201320 Hong Kong protests}}\n{{HKafter1997}}\n\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by dependent territory|Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic in China by city|Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Asia|Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:2020 in Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in Hong Kong]]\n", "name_user": "Ohconfucius", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBackground", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Hong_Kong"}
{"title_page": "We Need a Resolution", "text_new": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = We Need a Resolution\n| cover      = Aaliyah-WeNeedAResolutionCDSingle.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Aaliyah]] featuring [[Timbaland]]\n| album      = [[Aaliyah (album)|Aaliyah]]\n| B-side     = {{ubl|\"Messed Up\"|\"[[Are You Feelin' Me?]]\"}}\n| released   = April 13, 2001\n| format     = {{hlist|[[CD single]]|[[12-inch single|12\" single]]|[[cassette single|cassette]]}}\n| recorded   = March 2001; [[Westlake Recording Studios]]<br><small>([[Los Angeles]], [[California]])</small>\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]<ref>{{cite news|last=Edwards|first=Shawn|date=September 6, 2001|url=http://www.pitch.com/kansascity/aaliyah/Content?oid=2164081|title=Aaliyah|newspaper=[[The Pitch (newspaper)|The Pitch]]|location=Kansas City|accessdate=July 16, 2013}}</ref>\n| length     = 4:02\n| label      = {{hlist|[[Blackground Records|Blackground]]|[[Virgin Records|Virgin]]}}\n| writer     = {{hlist|[[Timbaland|Tim Mosley]]|[[Static Major|Stephen Garrett]]}}\n| producer   = Timbaland\n| chronology = [[Aaliyah]]\n| prev_title = [[Come Back in One Piece]]\n| prev_year  = 2000\n| next_title = [[More Than a Woman (Aaliyah song)|More Than a Woman]]\n| next_year  = 2001\n| misc       = {{Extra chronology\n | artist     = [[Timbaland]]\n | type       = singles\n | prev_title = Can't Nobody\n | prev_year  = 1999\n | title      = We Need a Resolution\n | year       = 2001\n | next_title = [[Ugly (Bubba Sparxxx song)|Ugly]]\n | next_year  = 2001\n}}\n}}\n\n\"'''We Need a Resolution'''\" is a song performed by American recording artist [[Aaliyah]]. It was written by [[Static Major]] and [[Timbaland]], who also produced and contributed a featured [[rapping|rap]]. The song was released on April 13, 2001, as the [[lead single]] for Aaliyah's self-titled 2001 album ''[[Aaliyah (album)|Aaliyah]]''.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Mitchell|first=Gail|page=43|date=April 7, 2001|volume=113|issue=14|title=MCA Takes On An Alluring Proposition; Aaliyah's New Album Now Set For June 5|journal=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|location=New York|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uBMEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA43#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=November 25, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe song was a moderate success internationally. \"We Need a Resolution\" reached the top 20 of the [[UK Singles Chart]] and the top 30 in [[Canada]]. In October 2011, ''[[NME]]'' placed it at number 119 on its list 150 Best Tracks of the Past 15 Years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/list/150-best-tracks-of-the-past-15-years/248648/page/4 |title=150 Best Tracks Of The Past 15 Years |publisher=Nme.Com |date= |accessdate=2012-03-14}}</ref> It was placed 21st on [[Slant Magazine]]'s Best of the Aughts: Singles list and 30th on [[Stylus Magazine]]'s Top 50 Singles: 2000\u20132005.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/music/feature/best-of-the-aughts-singles/214/page_8 |title=Best of the Aughts: Singles|publisher=slantmagazine.com|date= |accessdate=2010-01-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stylusmagazine.com/feature.php?ID=1419|title=The Top 50 Singles: 2000-2005|publisher=stylusmagazine.com|date= |accessdate=2012-10-15}}</ref> The single and the music video was also ranked 8th and 6th, respectively, on [[Slant Magazine]]'s Best Singles and Music Videos of 2001 list.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://barf.slantmagazine.com/music/feature/2001-year-in-music/176|title=2001: Year in Music|publisher=slantmagazine.com|accessdate=2012-10-15|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130202074018/http://barf.slantmagazine.com/music/feature/2001-year-in-music/176|archive-date=2013-02-02|url-status=dead}}</ref> [[dotmusic]] which was formally apart of \"Launch\" on yahoo felt that this song was another classy slice of experimental R&B produced by Aaliyah.<ref name=dm>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050122130547/http://uk.launch.yahoo.com:80/l_reviews_s/20916.html|title=Single Reviews Aaliyah-\"We Need A Resolution|date=July 11, 2001|work=[[dotmusic]]|accessdate=November 20, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nDuring the recording process for her third album Aaliyah was also filming her second movie ''[[Queen of the Damned]]'' in [[Australia]].<ref name=album>{{cite web|url=http://youknowigotsoul.com/aaliyah|title=Exclusive: The Producers of \"Aaliyah\" Take Us Behind the Scenes Into Making of This Classic - YouKnowIGotSoul.com|publisher=}}</ref> Due to her hectic schedule at that time, Aaliyah decided to record her album simultaneously while filming a movie.<ref name=album/> In order for it to be possible to record an album while filming a movie Aaliyah's team of producers traveled to Australia with her.<ref name=album/> Majority of the producers who are featured on the album went to Australia to with the exception of Timbaland.<ref name=album/> Due to unforeseen issues at that time with Blackground records Timbaland wasn't expected to appear on Aaliyah's album at all.<ref name=album/> According to Tim Barnett former assistant to songwriter Static Major \u201cWe went back to New York and did them in either Sound King or Manhattan studio. We did them right after the New Year. Part of the problem was Timbaland and Missy weren\u2019t even going to be on the album because of problems with Blackground. Aaliyah talked Tim into producing records for the album, so Timbaland did it out of love for Babygirl.\u201d<ref name=album/> Once Aaliyah reached out to Timbaland and asked him to produce songs for the album there were constant doubts about him meeting his deadline in time due to it being last minute.<ref name=album/> According to producer Rapture Stewart Timbaland came on board for the album during the last week before the album was finalized.<ref name=album/> Stewart also stated \"Timbaland was so busy that he wasn\u2019t able to do his songs until the last week and they didn\u2019t know if he was going to make it in time for him to do it\".<ref name=album/> Due to the uncertainty with Timbaland being able to make his deadline in time the song \"Loose Rap\" was chosen as the album's lead single.<ref name=album/> Once Timbaland submitted his songs within the deadline Aaliyah's record label decided that \"We Need a Resolution\" was going to be the lead single instead.<ref name=album/>\n\n==Composition and lyrical interpretation==\n\"We Need a Resolution\" has been described as having a \"seductive Middle Eastern vibe\"<ref name=\"Cinquemani\">{{cite web|last=Cinquemani|first=Sal|date=July 17, 2001|url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/music/review/aaliyah-aaliyah/1|title=Aaliyah: Aaliyah|publisher=[[Slant Magazine]]|accessdate=November 25, 2012}}</ref> \"as the backing track slithers along with an almost Egyptian feel\".<ref name=dm/> According to  Nateleg\u00e9 Whaley from [[Mic (media company)|Mic]] \"We Need a Resolution\" opens with warpy clarinet samples as Timbaland  dodges confrontation by repeatedly saying \"I'm tired of arguing girl.\"<ref name=\"mic\">{{cite web|last=Whaley|first=Nateleg\u00e9|date=July 7, 2016|url=https://mic.com/articles/148059/15-years-ago-aaliyah-s-intuitive-cool-became-a-blueprint-for-the-future-of-r-b#.cnihmgaWF|title=15 Years Ago,Aaliyah's Intuitive Cool Became a Blueprint for the Future of R&B|publisher=[[Mic (media company)|Mic]]|accessdate=December 10, 2018}}</ref> Aaliyah's first line in the song cuts to the chase, responding in a chill, direct manner: \"Did you sleep on the wrong side?/ I'm catching a bad vibe.\" <ref name=\"mic\"/>\n\nOn \"We Need a Resolution\" \"Timbaland combines idiosyncratic beats, moody, off-key melodies and an insistent, dirgelike chorus for a strangely hypnotic effect\".<ref name=debut>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/click-track/post/archives-remembering-aaliyah/2011/08/25/gIQAEjUwdJ_blog.html?noredirect=on|title=Aaliyah\u2019s Peek Performance|work=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=December 15, 2018}}</ref> Also the song's production has a sparse [[arrangement]] with stop-start [[drum pattern]]s and hand claps.<ref name=\"Hardy\"/> Lyrically the song maturely presents two perspectives in a passive-aggressive relationship.<ref name=\"Cinquemani\"/> Aaliyah's sinuously sung concerns are playfully dismissed in Timbaland's featured [[rapping|rap]].<ref name=\"Hardy\">{{cite journal|last=Hardy |first=Ernest |date=August 2, 2001 |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/recordings/review.asp?aid=2042779&cf=1967 |title=Recordings: Aaliyah, Aaliyah, 4 Stars |journal=[[Rolling Stone]] |location=New York |issue=874 |pages=61\u201362 |accessdate=November 24, 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020606031046/http://www.rollingstone.com/recordings/review.asp?aid=2042779&cf=1967 |archivedate=June 6, 2002 |url-status=unfit }}</ref> The song leaves its hook [[resolution (music)|unresolved]], plays backwards after Timbaland's rap, and concludes with a reversed [[loop (music)|loop]] of the vocal \"where were you last night\", which echoes the female protagonist's sentiment.<ref>{{harvnb|Clover|2001|p=130}}; {{harvnb|Cinquemani|2001}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\nChuck Taylor from [[Billboard magazine|Billboard]] gave the song a mixed review, although he praised Aaliyah's vocal delivery by saying, \"Aaliyah's light but direct delivery complements the hectic track well\" he ultimately felt that the overall song was classic Aaliyah and he expressed that he hoped that she would show more growth and variety just as well as she is building her budding acting resume.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BBQEAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA21&dq=aaliyah%20review&pg=PA21#v=onepage&q=aaliyah%20review&f=false|title=Reviews & Previews|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=November 20, 2018}}</ref> In a review of Aaliyah's eponymous album Michael Paoletta from Billboard described the song as being \"wickedly hypnotic\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-RMEAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA22&dq=Aaliyah%20Aaliyah%20review&pg=PA22#v=onepage&q=Aaliyah%20Aaliyah%20review&f=false|title=Reviews & Previews|date=July 28, 2001|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=December 30, 2018}}</ref> Damien Scott from [[Complex Magazine|Complex]] felt that the song was one of the strongest cuts from Aaliyah's self titled album and that it shows her being more grown and confident. He also felt that the song was both one of Aaliyah's best vocal performance and Timbland's best guest rap verses.<ref name=complex>{{cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/the-best-aaliyah-songs/we-need-a-resolution|title=The 25 Best Aaliyah Songs |date=May 19, 2016|work=[[Complex Magazine|Complex]]|accessdate=July 20, 2018}}</ref> Chris Heath from [[dotmusic]] praised the song by saying \"it's what's going on beneath the chorus and verse that makes We Need A Resolution such an alluring proposition\". He also felt that Aaliyah \"produced another classy slice of experimental R&B\".<ref name=dm/> Alexis Petridis from [[The Guardian]] felt that compared to other records played on Pop radio \"We Need a Resolution sounded like an unhinged experiment in sound, one that just happened to have an insistent, catchy chorus attached\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2001/aug/31/artsfeatures.popandrock|title=The princess of risk|work=[[The Guardian]]|last=Petridis|first=Alexis|date=August 31, 2001|accessdate=December 30, 2018}}</ref> In a review of her eponymous album Luke McManus from the Irish publication [[Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann|RTE]] felt that \"We Need a Resolution\" \" is a highlight - a heartfelt tale of domestic stress over backward loops, deranged arpeggios and a rare Timbaland appearance on the microphone\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rte.ie/entertainment/music-reviews/2001/0802/448509-aaliyah/|title=Aaliyah - Aaliyah|work=[[Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann|RTE]]|date=August 2, 2001|accessdate=December 30, 2018}}</ref> Daryl Easlea from [[BBC|BBC UK]] felt that the song demonstrated her strengths; According to Easlea stated, \"Opener We Need A Resolution \u2013 a duet with Timabland \u2013 demonstrates her strength. She was not a teenager anymore and the almost gothic setting over skeletal beats underlines this new maturity\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/reviews/2wjw/|title=Review of Aaliyah|work=[[BBC]]|accessdate=December 30, 2018}}</ref> Connie Johnson from the [[Los Angeles Times]] felt that \"We need a resolution\" along with \"Rock the Boat\" were stand out songs, compared to other artist material.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2001/jul/29/entertainment/ca-27750|title=A Coasting Aaliyah Steers Clear of Depth\n|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|accessdate=December 30, 2018}}</ref> Rich Bellis from [[The Atlantic]] praised Aaliyah's vocals on the song describing it as freaky \"that go from staccato to snake-charmer and a beat that hopscotches all over the place\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2012/09/aaliyahs-influential-afterlife/262387/|title=Aaliyah's Influential Afterlife|work=[[The Atlantic]]|accessdate=December 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Chart performance==\n\"We Need a Resolution\" entered the Billboard Hot 100 chart on June 2, 2001 at number 78, the song reached its peak at number 59 five weeks later on June 30, 2001.<ref>{{cite web|date=June 2, 2001|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-100/2001-06-02|title=Billboard Hot 100 |work=[[Billboard Magazine|Billboard]] |accessdate=June 9, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|date=June 30, 2001|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-100/2001-06-30|title=Billboard Hot 100 |work=[[Billboard Magazine|Billboard]] |accessdate=June 9, 2018}}</ref> On the Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs chart the song peaked within the top 20 at number 15 on June 30, 2001.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/Aaliyah/chart-history/r-b-hip-hop-songs|title=Billboard Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs |work=[[Billboard Magazine|Billboard]] |accessdate=June 9, 2018}}</ref>\nThe song also peaked within the top 40 on both the  Tropical Airplay and Rhythmic charts at number 31 and 38 respectively.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/Aaliyah/chart-history/tropical-songs|title=Billboard Tropical Songs |work=[[Billboard Magazine|Billboard]] |accessdate=June 9, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/Aaliyah/chart-history/rhythmic-40|title=Rhythmic |work=[[Billboard Magazine|Billboard]] |accessdate=June 9, 2018}}</ref> Elsewhere in North America the song peaked within the top 40 at number 26 in Canada.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/Aaliyah/chart-history/hot-canada-digital-song-sales|title=Hot Canadian Digital Song Sales |work=[[Billboard Magazine|Billboard]] |accessdate=June 9, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn Europe the song was a moderate hit peaking within the top 40 in several regions. In the UK \"We Need a Resolution\" peaked within the top 20 at number 20 on the official charts on July 21, 2001.<ref name=\"Aaliyah\">{{cite web | url=https://www.officialcharts.com/artist/5632/aaliyah/ | title=Aaliyah | publisher=[[Official Charts Company]] | accessdate=December 9, 2018}}</ref> On the UK Official Dance charts the song entered the charts within the top 20 at number 14 on July 14, 2001.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/charts/dance-singles-chart/20010715/104/|title=Official Dance Singles Chart Top 40|date=July 14, 2001|work=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=December 29, 2018}}</ref> The following week on July 22, 2001 the song reached its peak within the top 10 at number 6 on the dance charts.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/charts/dance-singles-chart/20010722/104/|title=Official Dance Singles Chart Top 40|date=July 22, 2001|work=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=December 29, 2018}}</ref> Meanwhile, on the UK official R&B charts the song peaked within the top 10 at number 6 on July 15, 2001.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/charts/r-and-b-singles-chart/20010923/114/|title=Official R&B Singles Chart Top 40|date=September 23, 2001|work=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=December 9, 2018}}</ref> According to the [[Official Charts Company]] \"We Need a Resolution\" is Aaliyah's eighth best selling single in the UK.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/more-than-a-woman-aaliyah-remembered-on-her-birthday__16126/|title=More Than A Woman: Aaliyah remembered on her birthday|last=Myers|first=Justin|date=January 16, 2018|work=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=December 10, 2018}}</ref>\nElsewhere in Europe in Belgium \"We Need a Resolution\" peaked within the top 40 at number 28 on the Ultra top Wallonia charts on September 29, 2001.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ultratop.be/fr/song/12bf/Aaliyah-feat.-Timbaland-We-Need-A-Resolution|title=AALIYAH FEAT. TIMBALAND - WE NEED A RESOLUTION|work=[[Ultratop]]}}</ref> In the Netherlands the song peaked within the top 5 at number 2 on the Tipparade chart on August 18, 2001.<ref name=tip>{{cite web|url=https://www.top40.nl/tipparade/2001/week-33|title=week 33 (18 augustus 2001)|language=Dutch|publisher=top40.nl}}</ref> Also in The Netherlands on the Single Top 100 chart the song peaked within the top 40 at number 37 on August 4, 2001.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dutchcharts.nl/showitem.asp?interpret=Aaliyah+feat.+Timbaland&titel=We+Need+a+Resolution&cat=s|title=AALIYAH FEAT. TIMBALAND - WE NEED A RESOLUTION|work=[[Single Top 100]]}}</ref>\n\n==Music video==\n\n===Background===\n[[File:Paul Hunter (cropped).jpg|right|thumb|upright|\"We Need a Resolution\" was the second music video that [[Paul Hunter (director)|Paul Hunter]] directed for Aaliyah.]]\n\nThe music video for \"We Need A Resolution\" was directed by [[Paul Hunter (director)|Paul Hunter]] in April 2001 in [[Los Angeles]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mvdbase.com/video.php?id=442|title=We Need a Resolution|accessdate=December 29, 2018|work=mvbase.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1442244/aaliyah-finds-resolution-with-new-single-video/|title=AALIYAH FINDS 'RESOLUTION' WITH NEW SINGLE, VIDEO|accessdate=August 2, 2018|work=[[MTV News]]}}</ref> Hunter had previously worked with Aaliyah in 1996 for her video \"One In a Million\".<ref name=resolution>{{cite web|url=https://www.vibe.com/2016/08/aaliyah-album-aaliyah-week|title=Aaliyah Week: Remembering Aaliyah's Final Musical Journey|work=[[Vibe Magazine|Vibe]]|last=Augustin|first=Camille|date=August 26, 2016|accessdate=December 8, 2018}}</ref> After directing the video for \"One In a Million\" Hunter wanted to work with Aaliyah again on other projects but it never came into fruition due to timing.<ref name=resolution/> According to Hunter \"We had a pretty good connection to other projects and both went our different ways [after shooting \u201cOne In A Million\u201d], I wanted to work with her on a couple of projects after that but she wanted to go in another direction\".<ref name=resolution/> After years of running into each other, Aaliyah reached out to Hunter during the recording of her third album and expressed that she wanted to work with him again.<ref name=resolution/> Her goal's for working with Hunter again was to recreate the \"magic\" that they had created with the \"One In a Million\" Video.<ref name=resolution/> Hunter explained \"She\u2019d gone her direction, I\u2019d gone my direction and then over time we started to see each other around and as she was making the record, she called me and said, \u2018Hey, I want to connect back with you on this project, try to recreate the magic that we did on \u201cOne In A Million\".<ref name=resolution/>\n\n===Theme===\nThe theme for \"We Need a Resolution\" was about taking an exclusive look into Aaliyah's life, the goal was to create an illusion that only certain people could see.<ref name=resolution/> According to Hunter \"One of the things that she wanted to do, she wanted to obviously dance, and she was really great at it. I felt that the idea behind that connection, we wanted an exclusive peek into her life, so the idea there was to create a sense that every room, every scenario that you\u2019re looking at something that only certain people can see\".<ref name=resolution/> When explaining the videos theme Hunter compared it to a celebrity in the airport.<ref name=resolution/> Hunter explained, \"It\u2019s almost like if you\u2019ve ever seen a celebrity in the airport, they\u2019re going into a first class lounge, or they\u2019re going into a private hallway, they sort of slip past you\".<ref name=resolution/> Ultimately Hunter wanted the theme for the music video to have an exclusive feel within every room and scene.<ref name=resolution/> For the video multiple snakes were used and the usage of snakes represented the idea of Danger.<ref name=resolution/> According to Hunter the idea to include snakes in the video were either Aaliyah's or his idea; the goal was to present Aaliyah being in control.<ref name=resolution/> Hunter stated, \"I think that idea was about danger. I don\u2019t know if it was her idea or my idea, but ultimately it was about her being in control of something that was dangerous or that would create some sort of tension in the story and that ultimately she was in control of it\u2026Aaliyah always wanted something that was different from what was going on\".<ref name=resolution/>\n\nIn an interview with [[MTV]] Aaliyah discussed her experience working with snakes for the video saying, \"I saw bags moving in the corner, And I found out they were real snakes. I was a little nervous, but I kinda like doing crazy stuff.\u201d<ref>{{cite web|url=https://people.com/archive/picks-and-pans-review-talking-with-aaliyah-vol-56-no-11/|title=Picks and Pans Review: Talking With...Aaliyah|work=[[People Magazine|People]]|date=September 10, 2001|accessdate=December 30, 2018}}</ref> Prior to working with snakes in her music video Aaliyah had previously worked with them for a photo shoot. According to Aaliyah \"I first dealt with snakes when I was in Australia and I did the photo shoot for the album. We used five pythons in the shoot. At first, I was a little nervous, but once I started to handle them, I totally fell in love and felt an affinity toward them. They're very mysterious creatures. They live in solitude, [and] there are times in my life [when] I just want to be by myself. There are times I can't even figure myself out. I feel they are very complex creatures, [but] at the same time, they're sexy, too. That's why they represent Aaliyah pretty well. They're dangerous, but quite beautiful. I thought that it would be an animal that could represent me on this album, so I wanted to take it from the photo shoot to the video and probably throughout the whole project.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.webcitation.org/6CnS2mJqd?url=http://www.mtv.com/bands/a/aaliyah/aaliyah01/index.jhtml|title=Aaliyah: Been a Long Time|work=[[MTV News]]|accessdate=December 30, 2018}}</ref> To uphold the snake theme for the video, Aaliyah is shown wearing fashion designer Gianfranco Ferr\u00e9's spring 2001 fringe reptile tube dress in one of the videos scene.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vogue.com/article/runwaytomusicvideo-instagram-account-identifies-clothes-in-hits|title=To Discover the Best Fashion in Music Videos, Head to This Instagram Account|work=[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]|last=SATENSTEIN|first=LIANA|date=October 15, 2018|accessdate=December 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Synopsis===\nThe video opens with Aaliyah sitting in a dark room in a black dress and also appearing on a TV screen performing the first verse. She is also shown sitting on a large question mark as it moves through a blue tunnel. Leading up to the chorus Aaliyah can be seen laying on a glass bed with headphones on. During the second verse and the next chorus she is in a scene with a snake around her neck in a [[snake pit]], wearing snakeskin underwear. As Timbaland's rap verse begins he can be seen in a dark room wearing shades. Aaliyah performs a dance routine with other dancers during Timbaland's verse, wearing a dragon T-shirt. The video closes with Aaliyah in the dark bedroom scene again and Aaliyah with one of the male dancers.\n\n===Reception===\nThe music video for \"We Need a Resolution\" made its television debut on the [[BET]] network during the week ending on April 22, 2001.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?rview=1&lr=&id=BBQEAAAAMBAJ&q=Aaliyah+we+need+a+resolution+mtv#v=snippet&q=Aaliyah%20we%20need%20a%20resolution%20mtv&f=false|title=Video Monitor|date=May 5, 2001|work=[[Billboard Magazine|Billboard]]|accessdate=December 28, 2018}}</ref>  During the week ending on April 29, 2001 the video made its debut on the [[MTV]] network.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?rview=1&lr=&id=FikEAAAAMBAJ&q=Aaliyah+we+need+a+resolution+mtv#v=snippet&q=Aaliyah%20we%20need%20a%20resolution%20mtv&f=false|title=Video Monitor|date=May 12, 2001|work=[[Billboard Magazine|Billboard]]|accessdate=December 28, 2018}}</ref> The following month later during the week ending on May 13, 2001 the video was the tenth most played video on MTV.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?rview=1&lr=&id=jhMEAAAAMBAJ&q=Aaliyah+we+need+a+resolution+mtv#v=snippet&q=Aaliyah%20we%20need%20a%20resolution%20mtv&f=false|title=Video Monitor|date=May 26, 2001|work=[[Billboard Magazine|Billboard]]|accessdate=December 28, 2018}}</ref> Also in May during the week ending of the 20th the video was the fifth most played video on BET.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DRQEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA115&dq=Aaliyah+we+need+a+resolution+MTV&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiS8eebg8TfAhX7ITQIHYOeCSoQ6AEINDAD#v=onepage&q=Aaliyah%20we%20need%20a%20resolution%20MTV&f=false|title=Video Monitor|date=June 2, 2001|work=[[Billboard Magazine|Billboard]]|accessdate=December 28, 2018}}</ref> Kathy Landoll from [[Vice (magazine)|Noisey Vice]] mentioned that Aaliyah \"adopted this sexy yet spacey motif, and we see it come to life in We Need A Resolution.\u201d<ref name=vice>{{cite web|url=https://noisey.vice.com/en_us/article/rgmamr/what-i-learned-about-style-from-aaliyahs-we-need-a-resolution|title=What I Learned About Style From Aaliyah\u2019s \"We Need A Resolution\"|date=January 16, 2014|work=[[Vice (magazine)|Noisey Vice]]|accessdate=December 30, 2018}}</ref> She also felt that the video captured Aaliyah's existence at the time, Landoll stated \"From see-through lace to gothic make up, and back around to one-dot lipstick application and free-flowing curls, \u201cWe Need A Revolution\u201d captured every angle of Aaliyah's existence at the time\".<ref name=vice/>\n\n==Charts==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Weekly charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!align=\"left\"|Chart (2001)\n!align=\"center\"|Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{singlechart|Australia|44|artist=Aaliyah feat. Timbaland|song=We Need a Resolution|accessdate=2014-12-09}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Flanders|47|artist=Aaliyah feat. Timbaland|song=We Need a Resolution |accessdate=2014-12-09}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Wallonia|28|artist=Aaliyah feat. Timbaland|song=We Need a Resolution |accessdate=2014-12-09}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"| Canada ([[Canadian Singles Chart|Nielsen SoundScan]])<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151108173958/http://www.billboard.com/artist/275352/aaliyah/chart?f=1186|title=Aaliyah - Chart history - Billboard|date=November 8, 2015|publisher=}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|26\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|Europe ([[European Hot 100 Singles]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Music-and-Media/00s/2001/MM-2001-07-28.pdf|title=Euro Chart Hot 100|work=Music & Media|page=7|date=July 28, 2001|accessdate=January 1, 2018}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|42\n|-\n{{singlechart|France|53|artist=Aaliyah feat. Timbaland|song=We Need a Resolution |accessdate=2014-12-09}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Germany2|66|artist=Aaliyah|song=We Need a Resolution|songid=4799|accessdate=2014-12-09}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Dutch100|37|artist=Aaliyah feat. Timbaland|song=We Need a Resolution |accessdate=2014-12-09}}\n|-\n|Netherlands ([[Tipparade]])<ref name=tip/>\n|align=\"center\"|2 \n|-\n{{singlechart|Scotland|44|date=20010902}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Sweden|46|artist=Aaliyah feat. Timbaland|song=We Need a Resolution |accessdate=2014-12-09}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Switzerland|56|artist=Aaliyah feat. Timbaland|song=We Need a Resolution |accessdate=2014-12-09}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|UKsinglesbyname|20|artist=Aaliyah|accessdate=November 29, 2017|artistid=5632}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|UKdance|10|date=20010812|accessdate=November 28, 2017}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|UKrandb|6|date=20010923|accessdate=March 4, 2016}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardhot100|59|artist=Aaliyah|accessdate=2013-02-24}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardrandbhiphop|15|artist=Aaliyah|accessdate=2011-05-05}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardrhythmic|38|artist=Aaliyah|accessdate=May 26, 2017}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardtropicalsongs|31|artist=Aaliyah|accessdate=October 12, 2017}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n=== Footnotes ===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n=== Bibliography ===\n* {{cite web|ref={{SfnRef|Cinquemani|2001}}|last=Cinquemani|first=Sal|date=October 15, 2001|url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/music/feature/2001-year-in-music/176|title=2001: Year in Music|publisher=Slant Magazine|accessdate=November 20, 2012}}\n* {{cite journal|ref=harv|last=Clover|first=Joshua|date=August 2001|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=f4iBwoaNrbcC&pg=PT10|title=Reviews|journal=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]|location=New York|volume=17|issue=8|accessdate=November 20, 2012}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{YouTube|qSlyL6m384Y|\"We Need a Resolution\"}}\n* {{MetroLyrics song|aaliyah|we-need-a-resolution}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{Aaliyah}}\n{{Timbaland singles}}\n\n[[Category:2001 singles]]\n[[Category:2001 songs]]\n[[Category:Aaliyah songs]]\n[[Category:Music videos directed by Paul Hunter (director)]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Timbaland]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Static Major]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Timbaland]]\n[[Category:Timbaland songs]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = We Need a Resolution\n| cover      = Aaliyah-WeNeedAResolutionCDSingle.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Aaliyah]] featuring [[Timbaland]]\n| album      = [[Aaliyah (album)|Aaliyah]]\n| B-side     = {{ubl|\"Messed Up\"|\"[[Are You Feelin' Me?]]\"}}\n| released   = April 13, 2001\n| format     = {{hlist|[[CD single]]|[[12-inch single|12\" single]]|[[cassette single|cassette]]}}\n| recorded   = March 2001; [[Westlake Recording Studios]]<br><small>([[Los Angeles]], [[California]])</small>\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]<ref>{{cite news|last=Edwards|first=Shawn|date=September 6, 2001|url=http://www.pitch.com/kansascity/aaliyah/Content?oid=2164081|title=Aaliyah|newspaper=[[The Pitch (newspaper)|The Pitch]]|location=Kansas City|accessdate=July 16, 2013}}</ref>\n| length     = 4:02\n| label      = {{hlist|[[Blackground Records|Blackground]]|[[Virgin Records|Virgin]]}}\n| writer     = {{hlist|[[Timbaland|Tim Mosley]]|[[Static Major|Stephen Garrett]]}}\n| producer   = Timbaland\n| chronology = [[Aaliyah]]\n| prev_title = [[Come Back in One Piece]]\n| prev_year  = 2000\n| next_title = [[More Than a Woman (Aaliyah song)|More Than a Woman]]\n| next_year  = 2001\n| misc       = {{Extra chronology\n | artist     = [[Timbaland]]\n | type       = singles\n | prev_title = Can't Nobody\n | prev_year  = 1999\n | title      = We Need a Resolution\n | year       = 2001\n | next_title = [[Ugly (Bubba Sparxxx song)|Ugly]]\n | next_year  = 2001\n}}\n}}\n\n\"'''We Need a Resolution'''\" is a song performed by American recording artist [[Aaliyah]]. It was written by [[Static Major]] and [[Timbaland]], who also produced and contributed a featured [[rapping|rap]]. The song was released on April 13, 2001, as the [[lead single]] for Aaliyah's self-titled 2001 album ''[[Aaliyah (album)|Aaliyah]]''.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Mitchell|first=Gail|page=43|date=April 7, 2001|volume=113|issue=14|title=MCA Takes On An Alluring Proposition; Aaliyah's New Album Now Set For June 5|journal=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|location=New York|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uBMEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA43#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=November 25, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe song was a moderate success internationally. \"We Need a Resolution\" reached the top 20 of the [[UK Singles Chart]] and the top 30 in [[Canada]]. In October 2011, ''[[NME]]'' placed it at number 119 on its list 150 Best Tracks of the Past 15 Years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/list/150-best-tracks-of-the-past-15-years/248648/page/4 |title=150 Best Tracks Of The Past 15 Years |publisher=Nme.Com |date= |accessdate=2012-03-14}}</ref> It was placed 21st on [[Slant Magazine]]'s Best of the Aughts: Singles list and 30th on [[Stylus Magazine]]'s Top 50 Singles: 2000\u20132005.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/music/feature/best-of-the-aughts-singles/214/page_8 |title=Best of the Aughts: Singles|publisher=slantmagazine.com|date= |accessdate=2010-01-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stylusmagazine.com/feature.php?ID=1419|title=The Top 50 Singles: 2000-2005|publisher=stylusmagazine.com|date= |accessdate=2012-10-15}}</ref> The single and the music video was also ranked 8th and 6th, respectively, on [[Slant Magazine]]'s Best Singles and Music Videos of 2001 list.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://barf.slantmagazine.com/music/feature/2001-year-in-music/176|title=2001: Year in Music|publisher=slantmagazine.com|accessdate=2012-10-15|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130202074018/http://barf.slantmagazine.com/music/feature/2001-year-in-music/176|archive-date=2013-02-02|url-status=dead}}</ref> [[dotmusic]] which was formally apart of \"Launch\" on yahoo felt that this song was another classy slice of experimental R&B produced by Aaliyah.<ref name=dm>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050122130547/http://uk.launch.yahoo.com:80/l_reviews_s/20916.html|title=Single Reviews Aaliyah-\"We Need A Resolution|date=July 11, 2001|work=[[dotmusic]]|accessdate=November 20, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nDuring the recording process for her third album Aaliyah was also filming her second movie ''[[Queen of the Damned]]'' in [[Australia]].<ref name=album>{{cite web|url=http://youknowigotsoul.com/aaliyah|title=Exclusive: The Producers of \"Aaliyah\" Take Us Behind the Scenes Into Making of This Classic - YouKnowIGotSoul.com|publisher=}}</ref> Due to her hectic schedule at that time, Aaliyah decided to record her album simultaneously while filming a movie.<ref name=album/> In order for it to be possible to record an album while filming a movie Aaliyah's team of producers traveled to Australia with her.<ref name=album/> Majority of the producers who are featured on the album went to Australia to with the exception of Timbaland.<ref name=album/> Due to unforeseen issues at that time with Blackground records Timbaland wasn't expected to appear on Aaliyah's album at all.<ref name=album/> According to Tim Barnett former assistant to songwriter Static Major \u201cWe went back to New York and did them in either Sound King or Manhattan studio. We did them right after the New Year. Part of the problem was Timbaland and Missy weren\u2019t even going to be on the album because of problems with Blackground. Aaliyah talked Tim into producing records for the album, so Timbaland did it out of love for Babygirl.\u201d<ref name=album/> Once Aaliyah reached out to Timbaland and asked him to produce songs for the album there were constant doubts about him meeting his deadline in time due to it being last minute.<ref name=album/> According to producer Rapture Stewart Timbaland came on board for the album during the last week before the album was finalized.<ref name=album/> Stewart also stated \"Timbaland was so busy that he wasn\u2019t able to do his songs until the last week and they didn\u2019t know if he was going to make it in time for him to do it\".<ref name=album/> Due to the uncertainty with Timbaland being able to make his deadline in time the song \"Loose Rap\" was chosen as the album's lead single.<ref name=album/> Once Timbaland submitted his songs within the deadline Aaliyah's record label decided that \"We Need a Resolution\" was going to be the lead single instead.<ref name=album/>\n\n==Composition and lyrical interpretation==\n\"We Need a Resolution\" has been described as having a \"seductive Middle Eastern vibe\"<ref name=\"Cinquemani\">{{cite web|last=Cinquemani|first=Sal|date=July 17, 2001|url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/music/review/aaliyah-aaliyah/1|title=Aaliyah: Aaliyah|publisher=[[Slant Magazine]]|accessdate=November 25, 2012}}</ref> \"as the backing track slithers along with an almost Egyptian feel\".<ref name=dm/> According to  Nateleg\u00e9 Whaley from [[Mic (media company)|Mic]] \"We Need a Resolution\" opens with warpy clarinet samples as Timbaland  dodges confrontation by repeatedly saying \"I'm tired of arguing girl.\"<ref name=\"mic\">{{cite web|last=Whaley|first=Nateleg\u00e9|date=July 7, 2016|url=https://mic.com/articles/148059/15-years-ago-aaliyah-s-intuitive-cool-became-a-blueprint-for-the-future-of-r-b#.cnihmgaWF|title=15 Years Ago,Aaliyah's Intuitive Cool Became a Blueprint for the Future of R&B|publisher=[[Mic (media company)|Mic]]|accessdate=December 10, 2018}}</ref> Aaliyah's first line in the song cuts to the chase, responding in a chill, direct manner: \"Did you sleep on the wrong side?/ I'm catching a bad vibe.\" <ref name=\"mic\"/>\n\nOn \"We Need a Resolution\" \"Timbaland combines idiosyncratic beats, moody, off-key melodies and an insistent, dirgelike chorus for a strangely hypnotic effect\".<ref name=debut>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/click-track/post/archives-remembering-aaliyah/2011/08/25/gIQAEjUwdJ_blog.html?noredirect=on|title=Aaliyah\u2019s Peek Performance|work=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=December 15, 2018}}</ref> Also the songs production has a sparse [[arrangement]] with stop-start [[drum pattern]]s and hand claps.<ref name=\"Hardy\"/> Lyrically the song maturely presents two perspectives in a passive-aggressive relationship.<ref name=\"Cinquemani\"/> Aaliyah's sinuously sung concerns are playfully dismissed in Timbaland's featured [[rapping|rap]].<ref name=\"Hardy\">{{cite journal|last=Hardy |first=Ernest |date=August 2, 2001 |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/recordings/review.asp?aid=2042779&cf=1967 |title=Recordings: Aaliyah, Aaliyah, 4 Stars |journal=[[Rolling Stone]] |location=New York |issue=874 |pages=61\u201362 |accessdate=November 24, 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020606031046/http://www.rollingstone.com/recordings/review.asp?aid=2042779&cf=1967 |archivedate=June 6, 2002 |url-status=unfit }}</ref> The song leaves its hook [[resolution (music)|unresolved]], plays backwards after Timbaland's rap, and concludes with a reversed [[loop (music)|loop]] of the vocal \"where were you last night\", which echoes the female protagonist's sentiment.<ref>{{harvnb|Clover|2001|p=130}}; {{harvnb|Cinquemani|2001}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\nChuck Taylor from [[Billboard magazine|Billboard]] gave the song a mixed review, although he praised Aaliyah's vocal delivery by saying, \"Aaliyah's light but direct delivery complements the hectic track well\" he ultimately felt that the overall song was classic Aaliyah and he expressed that he hoped that she would show more growth and variety just as well as she is building her budding acting resume.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BBQEAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA21&dq=aaliyah%20review&pg=PA21#v=onepage&q=aaliyah%20review&f=false|title=Reviews & Previews|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=November 20, 2018}}</ref> In a review of Aaliyah's eponymous album Michael Paoletta from Billboard described the song as being \"wickedly hypnotic\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-RMEAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA22&dq=Aaliyah%20Aaliyah%20review&pg=PA22#v=onepage&q=Aaliyah%20Aaliyah%20review&f=false|title=Reviews & Previews|date=July 28, 2001|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=December 30, 2018}}</ref> Damien Scott from [[Complex Magazine|Complex]] felt that the song was one of the strongest cuts from Aaliyah's self titled album and that it shows her being more grown and confident. He also felt that the song was both one of Aaliyah's best vocal performance and Timbland's best guest rap verses.<ref name=complex>{{cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/the-best-aaliyah-songs/we-need-a-resolution|title=The 25 Best Aaliyah Songs |date=May 19, 2016|work=[[Complex Magazine|Complex]]|accessdate=July 20, 2018}}</ref> Chris Heath from [[dotmusic]] praised the song by saying \"it's what's going on beneath the chorus and verse that makes We Need A Resolution such an alluring proposition\". He also felt that Aaliyah \"produced another classy slice of experimental R&B\".<ref name=dm/> Alexis Petridis from [[The Guardian]] felt that compared to other records played on Pop radio \"We Need a Resolution sounded like an unhinged experiment in sound, one that just happened to have an insistent, catchy chorus attached\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2001/aug/31/artsfeatures.popandrock|title=The princess of risk|work=[[The Guardian]]|last=Petridis|first=Alexis|date=August 31, 2001|accessdate=December 30, 2018}}</ref> In a review of her eponymous album Luke McManus from the Irish publication [[Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann|RTE]] felt that \"We Need a Resolution\" \" is a highlight - a heartfelt tale of domestic stress over backward loops, deranged arpeggios and a rare Timbaland appearance on the microphone\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rte.ie/entertainment/music-reviews/2001/0802/448509-aaliyah/|title=Aaliyah - Aaliyah|work=[[Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann|RTE]]|date=August 2, 2001|accessdate=December 30, 2018}}</ref> Daryl Easlea from [[BBC|BBC UK]] felt that the song demonstrated her strengths; According to Easlea stated, \"Opener We Need A Resolution \u2013 a duet with Timabland \u2013 demonstrates her strength. She was not a teenager anymore and the almost gothic setting over skeletal beats underlines this new maturity\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/reviews/2wjw/|title=Review of Aaliyah|work=[[BBC]]|accessdate=December 30, 2018}}</ref> Connie Johnson from the [[Los Angeles Times]] felt that \"We need a resolution\" along with \"Rock the Boat\" were stand out songs, compared to other artist material.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2001/jul/29/entertainment/ca-27750|title=A Coasting Aaliyah Steers Clear of Depth\n|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|accessdate=December 30, 2018}}</ref> Rich Bellis from [[The Atlantic]] praised Aaliyah's vocals on the song describing it as freaky \"that go from staccato to snake-charmer and a beat that hopscotches all over the place\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2012/09/aaliyahs-influential-afterlife/262387/|title=Aaliyah's Influential Afterlife|work=[[The Atlantic]]|accessdate=December 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Chart performance==\n\"We Need a Resolution\" entered the Billboard Hot 100 chart on June 2, 2001 at number 78, the song reached its peak at number 59 five weeks later on June 30, 2001.<ref>{{cite web|date=June 2, 2001|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-100/2001-06-02|title=Billboard Hot 100 |work=[[Billboard Magazine|Billboard]] |accessdate=June 9, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|date=June 30, 2001|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-100/2001-06-30|title=Billboard Hot 100 |work=[[Billboard Magazine|Billboard]] |accessdate=June 9, 2018}}</ref> On the Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs chart the song peaked within the top 20 at number 15 on June 30, 2001.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/Aaliyah/chart-history/r-b-hip-hop-songs|title=Billboard Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs |work=[[Billboard Magazine|Billboard]] |accessdate=June 9, 2018}}</ref>\nThe song also peaked within the top 40 on both the  Tropical Airplay and Rhythmic charts at number 31 and 38 respectively.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/Aaliyah/chart-history/tropical-songs|title=Billboard Tropical Songs |work=[[Billboard Magazine|Billboard]] |accessdate=June 9, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/Aaliyah/chart-history/rhythmic-40|title=Rhythmic |work=[[Billboard Magazine|Billboard]] |accessdate=June 9, 2018}}</ref> Elsewhere in North America the song peaked within the top 40 at number 26 in Canada.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/Aaliyah/chart-history/hot-canada-digital-song-sales|title=Hot Canadian Digital Song Sales |work=[[Billboard Magazine|Billboard]] |accessdate=June 9, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn Europe the song was a moderate hit peaking within the top 40 in several regions. In the UK \"We Need a Resolution\" peaked within the top 20 at number 20 on the official charts on July 21, 2001.<ref name=\"Aaliyah\">{{cite web | url=https://www.officialcharts.com/artist/5632/aaliyah/ | title=Aaliyah | publisher=[[Official Charts Company]] | accessdate=December 9, 2018}}</ref> On the UK Official Dance charts the song entered the charts within the top 20 at number 14 on July 14, 2001.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/charts/dance-singles-chart/20010715/104/|title=Official Dance Singles Chart Top 40|date=July 14, 2001|work=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=December 29, 2018}}</ref> The following week on July 22, 2001 the song reached its peak within the top 10 at number 6 on the dance charts.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/charts/dance-singles-chart/20010722/104/|title=Official Dance Singles Chart Top 40|date=July 22, 2001|work=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=December 29, 2018}}</ref> Meanwhile, on the UK official R&B charts the song peaked within the top 10 at number 6 on July 15, 2001.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/charts/r-and-b-singles-chart/20010923/114/|title=Official R&B Singles Chart Top 40|date=September 23, 2001|work=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=December 9, 2018}}</ref> According to the [[Official Charts Company]] \"We Need a Resolution\" is Aaliyah's eighth best selling single in the UK.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/more-than-a-woman-aaliyah-remembered-on-her-birthday__16126/|title=More Than A Woman: Aaliyah remembered on her birthday|last=Myers|first=Justin|date=January 16, 2018|work=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=December 10, 2018}}</ref>\nElsewhere in Europe in Belgium \"we Need a Resoultion\" peaked within the top 40 at number 28 on the Ultra top Wallonia charts on September 29, 2001.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ultratop.be/fr/song/12bf/Aaliyah-feat.-Timbaland-We-Need-A-Resolution|title=AALIYAH FEAT. TIMBALAND - WE NEED A RESOLUTION|work=[[Ultratop]]}}</ref> In the Netherlands the song peaked within the top 5 at number 2 on the Tipparade chart on August 18, 2001.<ref name=tip>{{cite web|url=https://www.top40.nl/tipparade/2001/week-33|title=week 33 (18 augustus 2001)|language=Dutch|publisher=top40.nl}}</ref> Also in The Netherlands on the Single Top 100 chart the song peaked within the top 40 at number 37 on August 4, 2001.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dutchcharts.nl/showitem.asp?interpret=Aaliyah+feat.+Timbaland&titel=We+Need+a+Resolution&cat=s|title=AALIYAH FEAT. TIMBALAND - WE NEED A RESOLUTION|work=[[Single Top 100]]}}</ref>\n\n==Music video==\n\n===Background===\n[[File:Paul Hunter (cropped).jpg|right|thumb|upright|\"We Need a Resolution\" was the second music video that [[Paul Hunter (director)|Paul Hunter]] directed for Aaliyah.]]\n\nThe music video for \"We Need A Resolution\" was directed by [[Paul Hunter (director)|Paul Hunter]] in April 2001 in [[Los Angeles]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mvdbase.com/video.php?id=442|title=We Need a Resolution|accessdate=December 29, 2018|work=mvbase.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1442244/aaliyah-finds-resolution-with-new-single-video/|title=AALIYAH FINDS 'RESOLUTION' WITH NEW SINGLE, VIDEO|accessdate=August 2, 2018|work=[[MTV News]]}}</ref> Hunter had previously worked with Aaliyah in 1996 for her video \"One In a Million\".<ref name=resolution>{{cite web|url=https://www.vibe.com/2016/08/aaliyah-album-aaliyah-week|title=Aaliyah Week: Remembering Aaliyah's Final Musical Journey|work=[[Vibe Magazine|Vibe]]|last=Augustin|first=Camille|date=August 26, 2016|accessdate=December 8, 2018}}</ref> After directing the video for \"One In a Million\" Hunter wanted to work with Aaliyah again on other projects but it never came into fruition due to timing.<ref name=resolution/> According to Hunter \"We had a pretty good connection to other projects and both went our different ways [after shooting \u201cOne In A Million\u201d], I wanted to work with her on a couple of projects after that but she wanted to go in another direction\".<ref name=resolution/> After years of running into each other, Aaliyah reached out to Hunter during the recording of her third album and expressed that she wanted to work with him again.<ref name=resolution/> Her goal's for working with Hunter again was to recreate the \"magic\" that they had created with the \"One In a Million\" Video.<ref name=resolution/> Hunter explained \"She\u2019d gone her direction, I\u2019d gone my direction and then over time we started to see each other around and as she was making the record, she called me and said, \u2018Hey, I want to connect back with you on this project, try to recreate the magic that we did on \u201cOne In A Million\".<ref name=resolution/>\n\n===Theme===\nThe theme for \"We Need a Resolution\" was about taking an exclusive look into Aaliyah's life, the goal was to create an illusion that only certain people could see.<ref name=resolution/> According to Hunter \"One of the things that she wanted to do, she wanted to obviously dance, and she was really great at it. I felt that the idea behind that connection, we wanted an exclusive peek into her life, so the idea there was to create a sense that every room, every scenario that you\u2019re looking at something that only certain people can see\".<ref name=resolution/> When explaining the videos theme Hunter compared it to a celebrity in the airport.<ref name=resolution/> Hunter explained, \"It\u2019s almost like if you\u2019ve ever seen a celebrity in the airport, they\u2019re going into a first class lounge, or they\u2019re going into a private hallway, they sort of slip past you\".<ref name=resolution/> Ultimately Hunter wanted the theme for the music video to have an exclusive feel within every room and scene.<ref name=resolution/> For the video multiple snakes were used and the usage of snakes represented the idea of Danger.<ref name=resolution/> According to Hunter the idea to include snakes in the video were either Aaliyah's or his idea; the goal was to present Aaliyah being in control.<ref name=resolution/> Hunter stated, \"I think that idea was about danger. I don\u2019t know if it was her idea or my idea, but ultimately it was about her being in control of something that was dangerous or that would create some sort of tension in the story and that ultimately she was in control of it\u2026Aaliyah always wanted something that was different from what was going on\".<ref name=resolution/>\n\nIn an interview with [[MTV]] Aaliyah discussed her experience working with snakes for the video saying, \"I saw bags moving in the corner, And I found out they were real snakes. I was a little nervous, but I kinda like doing crazy stuff.\u201d<ref>{{cite web|url=https://people.com/archive/picks-and-pans-review-talking-with-aaliyah-vol-56-no-11/|title=Picks and Pans Review: Talking With...Aaliyah|work=[[People Magazine|People]]|date=September 10, 2001|accessdate=December 30, 2018}}</ref> Prior to working with snakes in her music video Aaliyah had previously worked with them for a photo shoot. According to Aaliyah \"I first dealt with snakes when I was in Australia and I did the photo shoot for the album. We used five pythons in the shoot. At first, I was a little nervous, but once I started to handle them, I totally fell in love and felt an affinity toward them. They're very mysterious creatures. They live in solitude, [and] there are times in my life [when] I just want to be by myself. There are times I can't even figure myself out. I feel they are very complex creatures, [but] at the same time, they're sexy, too. That's why they represent Aaliyah pretty well. They're dangerous, but quite beautiful. I thought that it would be an animal that could represent me on this album, so I wanted to take it from the photo shoot to the video and probably throughout the whole project.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.webcitation.org/6CnS2mJqd?url=http://www.mtv.com/bands/a/aaliyah/aaliyah01/index.jhtml|title=Aaliyah: Been a Long Time|work=[[MTV News]]|accessdate=December 30, 2018}}</ref> To uphold the snake theme for the video, Aaliyah is shown wearing fashion designer Gianfranco Ferr\u00e9's spring 2001 fringe reptile tube dress in one of the videos scene.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vogue.com/article/runwaytomusicvideo-instagram-account-identifies-clothes-in-hits|title=To Discover the Best Fashion in Music Videos, Head to This Instagram Account|work=[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]|last=SATENSTEIN|first=LIANA|date=October 15, 2018|accessdate=December 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Synopsis===\nThe video opens with Aaliyah sitting in a dark room in a black dress and also appearing on a TV screen performing the first verse. She is also shown sitting on a large question mark as it moves through a blue tunnel. Leading up to the chorus Aaliyah can be seen laying on a glass bed with headphones on. During the second verse and the next chorus she is in a scene with a snake around her neck in a [[snake pit]], wearing snakeskin underwear. As Timbaland's rap verse begins he can be seen in a dark room wearing shades. Aaliyah performs a dance routine with other dancers during Timbaland's verse, wearing a dragon T-shirt. The video closes with Aaliyah in the dark bedroom scene again and Aaliyah with one of the male dancers.\n\n===Reception===\nThe music video for \"We Need a Resolution\" made its television debut on the [[BET]] network during the week ending on April 22, 2001.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?rview=1&lr=&id=BBQEAAAAMBAJ&q=Aaliyah+we+need+a+resolution+mtv#v=snippet&q=Aaliyah%20we%20need%20a%20resolution%20mtv&f=false|title=Video Monitor|date=May 5, 2001|work=[[Billboard Magazine|Billboard]]|accessdate=December 28, 2018}}</ref>  During the week ending on April 29, 2001 the video made its debut on the [[MTV]] network.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?rview=1&lr=&id=FikEAAAAMBAJ&q=Aaliyah+we+need+a+resolution+mtv#v=snippet&q=Aaliyah%20we%20need%20a%20resolution%20mtv&f=false|title=Video Monitor|date=May 12, 2001|work=[[Billboard Magazine|Billboard]]|accessdate=December 28, 2018}}</ref> The following month later during the week ending on May 13, 2001 the video was the tenth most played video on MTV.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?rview=1&lr=&id=jhMEAAAAMBAJ&q=Aaliyah+we+need+a+resolution+mtv#v=snippet&q=Aaliyah%20we%20need%20a%20resolution%20mtv&f=false|title=Video Monitor|date=May 26, 2001|work=[[Billboard Magazine|Billboard]]|accessdate=December 28, 2018}}</ref> Also in May during the week ending of the 20th the video was the fifth most played video on BET.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DRQEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA115&dq=Aaliyah+we+need+a+resolution+MTV&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiS8eebg8TfAhX7ITQIHYOeCSoQ6AEINDAD#v=onepage&q=Aaliyah%20we%20need%20a%20resolution%20MTV&f=false|title=Video Monitor|date=June 2, 2001|work=[[Billboard Magazine|Billboard]]|accessdate=December 28, 2018}}</ref> Kathy Landoll from [[Vice (magazine)|Noisey Vice]] mentioned that Aaliyah \"adopted this sexy yet spacey motif, and we see it come to life in We Need A Resolution.\u201d<ref name=vice>{{cite web|url=https://noisey.vice.com/en_us/article/rgmamr/what-i-learned-about-style-from-aaliyahs-we-need-a-resolution|title=What I Learned About Style From Aaliyah\u2019s \"We Need A Resolution\"|date=January 16, 2014|work=[[Vice (magazine)|Noisey Vice]]|accessdate=December 30, 2018}}</ref> She also felt that the video captured Aaliyah's existence at the time, Landoll stated \"From see-through lace to gothic make up, and back around to one-dot lipstick application and free-flowing curls, \u201cWe Need A Revolution\u201d captured every angle of Aaliyah's existence at the time\".<ref name=vice/>\n\n==Charts==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Weekly charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!align=\"left\"|Chart (2001)\n!align=\"center\"|Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{singlechart|Australia|44|artist=Aaliyah feat. Timbaland|song=We Need a Resolution|accessdate=2014-12-09}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Flanders|47|artist=Aaliyah feat. Timbaland|song=We Need a Resolution |accessdate=2014-12-09}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Wallonia|28|artist=Aaliyah feat. Timbaland|song=We Need a Resolution |accessdate=2014-12-09}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"| Canada ([[Canadian Singles Chart|Nielsen SoundScan]])<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151108173958/http://www.billboard.com/artist/275352/aaliyah/chart?f=1186|title=Aaliyah - Chart history - Billboard|date=November 8, 2015|publisher=}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|26\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|Europe ([[European Hot 100 Singles]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Music-and-Media/00s/2001/MM-2001-07-28.pdf|title=Euro Chart Hot 100|work=Music & Media|page=7|date=July 28, 2001|accessdate=January 1, 2018}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|42\n|-\n{{singlechart|France|53|artist=Aaliyah feat. Timbaland|song=We Need a Resolution |accessdate=2014-12-09}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Germany2|66|artist=Aaliyah|song=We Need a Resolution|songid=4799|accessdate=2014-12-09}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Dutch100|37|artist=Aaliyah feat. Timbaland|song=We Need a Resolution |accessdate=2014-12-09}}\n|-\n|Netherlands ([[Tipparade]])<ref name=tip/>\n|align=\"center\"|2 \n|-\n{{singlechart|Scotland|44|date=20010902}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Sweden|46|artist=Aaliyah feat. Timbaland|song=We Need a Resolution |accessdate=2014-12-09}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Switzerland|56|artist=Aaliyah feat. Timbaland|song=We Need a Resolution |accessdate=2014-12-09}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|UKsinglesbyname|20|artist=Aaliyah|accessdate=November 29, 2017|artistid=5632}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|UKdance|10|date=20010812|accessdate=November 28, 2017}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|UKrandb|6|date=20010923|accessdate=March 4, 2016}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardhot100|59|artist=Aaliyah|accessdate=2013-02-24}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardrandbhiphop|15|artist=Aaliyah|accessdate=2011-05-05}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardrhythmic|38|artist=Aaliyah|accessdate=May 26, 2017}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardtropicalsongs|31|artist=Aaliyah|accessdate=October 12, 2017}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n=== Footnotes ===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n=== Bibliography ===\n* {{cite web|ref={{SfnRef|Cinquemani|2001}}|last=Cinquemani|first=Sal|date=October 15, 2001|url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/music/feature/2001-year-in-music/176|title=2001: Year in Music|publisher=Slant Magazine|accessdate=November 20, 2012}}\n* {{cite journal|ref=harv|last=Clover|first=Joshua|date=August 2001|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=f4iBwoaNrbcC&pg=PT10|title=Reviews|journal=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]|location=New York|volume=17|issue=8|accessdate=November 20, 2012}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{YouTube|qSlyL6m384Y|\"We Need a Resolution\"}}\n* {{MetroLyrics song|aaliyah|we-need-a-resolution}}<!-- Licens